[{"id":44382,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["275","250","225","200"],"answer":2,"solution":"For an open organ pipe, the $n$-th harmonic frequency is $f_n = n \\cdot \\frac{v}{2L}$.<br>The 3rd harmonic is $v_3 = 3 \\cdot \\frac{330}{2L}$ and the 6th harmonic is $v_6 = 6 \\cdot \\frac{330}{2L}$.<br>Taking the difference: $v_6 - v_3 = (6-3) \\cdot \\frac{330}{2L} = 3 \\cdot \\frac{330}{2L} = 2200$.<br>Solving for $L$: $L = \\frac{3 \\times 330}{2 \\times 2200} = \\frac{990}{4400} = 0.225$ m = 225 mm.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44469,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>S</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mrow><mi>P</mi><msup><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfrac><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>V</mi></mfrac></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mrow><mi>P</mi><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>&#969;</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>300</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8771;</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mi>mm</mi></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44470,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2200</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>550</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>24</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mi>&#955;</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>330</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow><mn>15</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2200</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44525,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>200</mn><mo>.5</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>770</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>Hz</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>188</mn><mo>.5</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>178</mn><mo>.2</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math> <mrow> <math> <mi>f</mi> </math> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <math> <mi>V</mi> </math> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mi>ℓ</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mi>ℓ</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <msqrt> <mfrac> <mrow> <math> <mi>T</mi> </math> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>μ</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> </msqrt> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mi>ℓ</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <msqrt> <mfrac> <mrow> <math> <mi>T</mi> </math> </mrow> <mrow> <math> <mrow> <mi>A</mi><mi>d</mi></mrow> </math> </mrow> </mfrac> </msqrt> </mrow> </math><br /><br />Also, <math> <mrow> <math> <mi>Y</mi> </math> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <math> <mi>T</mi> </math> <mi>ℓ</mi> </mrow> <mrow> <math> <mi>A</mi> </math> <mo>Δ</mo> <mi>ℓ</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;⇒&nbsp;&nbsp;</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <math> <mi>T</mi> </math> </mrow> <mrow> <math> <mi>A</mi> </math> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <math> <mi>Y</mi> </math> <mo>Δ</mo> <mi>ℓ</mi> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>ℓ</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;⇒&nbsp;&nbsp;</mo> <math> <mi>f</mi> </math> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mi>ℓ</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <msqrt> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>Y</mtext> <mo>Δ</mo> <mi>ℓ</mi> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>ℓ</mi> <mtext>d</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </msqrt> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mi>ℓ</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>1.5 m,&nbsp;</mtext> <mfrac> <mrow> <mo>Δ</mo> <mi>ℓ</mi> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>ℓ</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>0.01, d</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>7.7</mtext> <mo>×</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mn>3&nbsp;</mn>&nbsp;</msup><mtext>kg</mtext> <mo>/</mo> <msup> <mtext>m</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mtext>Y</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>2.2</mtext> <mo>×</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mn>1&nbsp;</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mtext>N</mtext> <mo>/</mo> <msup> <mtext>m</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </math><br /><br />After solving<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <math> <mi>f</mi> </math> <mo>=</mo> <msqrt> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>7</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> </msqrt> <mo>×</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <math> <mrow> <mtext>H</mtext><mtext>z</mtext></mrow> </math> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <math> <mi>f</mi> </math> <mo>&nbsp;≈&nbsp;</mo> <mtext>178.2&nbsp;</mtext><math> <mrow> <mtext>H</mtext><mtext>z</mtext></mrow> </math> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":44375,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The standard equation of a transverse wave is given by $y = A\\sin(\\omega t + kx + \\phi)$<br><br>Comparing this with the given equation $y = 3\\sin(36t + 0.018x + \\pi/4)$, we get the wave number $k = 0.018 \\text{ cm}^{-1}$.<br><br>The least distance between two successive crests is the wavelength $\\lambda$ of the wave.<br><br>We know that $k = \\dfrac{2\\pi}{\\lambda}$<br><br>$\\lambda = \\dfrac{2\\pi}{k} = \\dfrac{2 \\times 3.14}{0.018}$<br><br>$\\lambda = \\dfrac{6.28}{0.018} = \\dfrac{6280}{18} = 348.88 \\text{ cm}$<br><br>Rounding to the nearest integer, we get $349 \\text{ cm}$.<br><br>Answer: $349$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44420,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Displacement equation of second wave can be written as,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mfenced><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mfenced><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mfenced><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi>sin</mi><mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>As we can see, the phase difference between the waves is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math>. Therefore, resultant amplitude will be sum of the amplitudes of the waves.</p><p>So <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44512,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["Graph A with slope <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math>","Graph A with slope  <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math>","Graph B with slope  <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math>","Graph B with slope  <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EM0102249.jpg\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 69px;\" /><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>p</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math><br /></br><math><mo>⇒</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math><br /></br>On comparing with <math><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math> and <math><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>⇒</mo></math> Graph with +ve slope and +ve intercept.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":44506,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>3</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>p</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>p</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;be the number of antinodes of both wires.</p><p>Fundamental frequency remains the same for both wires.&nbsp;<br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>same</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>same</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>same</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi>&#961;</mi></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p>From the above equation, we have&nbsp;<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>p</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msqrt><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>p</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msqrt><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi></msqrt></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>p</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>p</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><msqrt><mfrac><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></msqrt></math><br /><br />The ratio of antinodes is&nbsp;<math><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>.&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":44539,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["$460 \\mathrm{~ms}^{-1}$","$500 \\mathrm{~ms}^{-1}$","$650 \\mathrm{~ms}^{-1}$","None of these"],"answer":3,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& v=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma R T}{M}} \\\\\n& \\frac{V_1}{V_2}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma_1 M_2}{\\gamma_2 M_1}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\frac{7}{5} \\times 4}{\\frac{5}{3} \\times 32}} \\\\\n& \\frac{460}{V_2}=\\sqrt{\\frac{21}{25 \\times 8}} \\Rightarrow \\quad v_2=\\frac{460 \\times 5 \\times 2 \\sqrt{2}}{\\sqrt{21}}=1420\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":44406,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The fundamental frequency is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>.</p><p>The length of the&nbsp;string is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Linear mass density is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>m</mi><mi>l</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Using&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mi>&#955;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>18</mn></mrow><mn>20</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44385,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["$\\sqrt{2}$","2","8","4"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & v=\\sqrt{\\frac{T}{\\mu}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{T}{f \\pi R^2}} \\\\ & \\frac{v_2}{v_1}=\\frac{R_1}{R_2}=2\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (8 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44474,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>44</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>X</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#8467;</mi></mrow></mfrac><msqrt><mfrac><msub><mi>T</mi><mi>X</mi></msub><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac></msqrt></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>Z</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#8467;</mi></mrow></mfrac><msqrt><mfrac><msub><mi>T</mi><mi>Z</mi></msub><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac></msqrt></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><mfrac><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>X</mi></msub><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>Z</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>450</mn><mn>300</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><msub><mi>T</mi><mi>X</mi></msub><msub><mi>T</mi><mi>Z</mi></msub></mfrac></msqrt></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/></mtr></mtable></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mi>X</mi></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mi>Z</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44379,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["increase by 64 times","increase by 8 times","decrease by 4 times","decrease by 8 times"],"answer":2,"solution":"For a point source, intensity is given by $I = \\frac{P}{4\\pi r^2}$ where $P$ is power and $r$ is distance.<br>If the volume of the spherical detector increases by 8 times, then $\\frac{4}{3}\\pi r_{new}^3 = 8 \\cdot \\frac{4}{3}\\pi r_{old}^3$, giving $r_{new} = 2r_{old}$.<br>The new intensity is $I_{new} = \\frac{P}{4\\pi (2r_{old})^2} = \\frac{1}{4} \\cdot \\frac{P}{4\\pi r_{old}^2} = \\frac{I_{old}}{4}$.<br>Therefore intensity decreases by 4 times.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44535,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["$4.0 \\mathrm{~N}$","$12.5 \\mathrm{~N}$","$0.5 \\mathrm{~N}$","$6.25 \\mathrm{~N}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{T}=\\mu \\mathrm{v}^2=\\mu \\frac{\\omega^2}{\\mathrm{k}^2}=0.04 \\frac{(2 \\pi / 0.004)^2}{(2 \\pi / 0.50)^2}=6.25 \\mathrm{~N}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":44415,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The formula for the frequency in an open organ pipe is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Since, it is a second harmonic,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p>The frequency of the second harmonic becomes&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mi>L</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>The data given is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>360</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Substituting the values in the frequency formula</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>360</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>900</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44380,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["3","4","1","2"],"answer":3,"solution":"Fifth harmonic of closed organ pipe equals first harmonic of open pipe:<br>$f_{5\\text{ closed}} = f_{1\\text{ open}}$<br>$\\frac{5v}{4L_{\\text{closed}}} = \\frac{v}{2L_{\\text{open}}}$<br>$\\frac{L_{\\text{closed}}}{L_{\\text{open}}} = \\frac{5}{2}$<br>Since the ratio is $\\frac{5}{x}$, we get $x = 2$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44413,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The formula to calculate the fundamental frequency produced in a vibrating string is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>For the first case, it can be written that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>120</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>(</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Similarly, for the second case, it can be written that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>180</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>(</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>3</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Divide equation (3) by equation (2) and solve to obtain the required length of the string.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mn>180</mn><mn>120</mn></mfrac></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mi>L</mi></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mn>90</mn></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>90</mn><mi>L</mi></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>120</mn><mn>180</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>60</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44404,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Fundamental frequency for closed organ pipe in the first part:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>⇒</mo><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>11</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>Similarly, for second part:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>110</mn><mo>⇒</mo><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>Therefore, change in length <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Δ</mi><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>Change in volume <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>AΔ</mi><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>400</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>400</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>∵</mo><mi>ρ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44409,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>421</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>471</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>485</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>514</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c6777cc0-68c6-4136-a30a-efd4a8bf9cd8.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 47px;\" /></p><p>Let velocity of sound in air be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>. Using Doppler formula,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>o</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>s</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>40</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>400</mn><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>360</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>40</mn></mrow><mn>340</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>471</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44540,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["$\\alpha=25.00 \\pi, \\beta=\\pi$","$\\alpha=\\frac{0.08}{\\pi}, \\frac{2.0}{\\pi}$","$\\alpha=\\frac{0.04}{\\pi}, \\beta=\\frac{1.0}{\\pi}$","$\\alpha=12.50 \\pi, \\beta=\\frac{\\pi}{2.0}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$$\ny=0.005 \\cos (\\alpha x-\\beta \\mathrm{t})\n$$\ncomparing the equation with the standard form,\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& y=A \\cos \\left[\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{x}}{\\lambda}-\\frac{\\mathrm{t}}{\\mathrm{T}}\\right) 2 \\pi\\right] \\\\\n& 2 \\pi / \\lambda=\\alpha \\text { and } 2 \\pi / T=\\beta \\\\\n& \\alpha=2 \\pi / 0.08=25.00 \\pi \\\\\n& \\beta=\\pi\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":44531,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["(iii, iv), (i, ii)","(i, iii), (ii, iv)","(i, iv), (ii, iii)","(i, ii), (iii, iv)"],"answer":3,"solution":"In case of destructive interference Phase difference $\\phi=180^{\\circ}$ or $\\pi$ So wave pair (i) and (ii) will produce destructive interference.\nStationary or standing waves will produce by equations (iii) \\& (iv) as two waves travelling along the same line but in opposite direction.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":44401,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>310</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>333</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>341</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>325</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The speed of sound is given by, </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mi>γ</mi><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><mi>M</mi></mfrac></msqrt><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>273</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>32</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>314</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8541</mn><mo>≃</mo><mn>315</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Nearest answer given in the option is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>310</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44521,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["At $36 \\mathrm{~cm}$ and $84 \\mathrm{~cm}$ from one end","At $24 \\mathrm{~cm}$ and $72 \\mathrm{~cm}$ from one end","At $48 \\mathrm{~cm}$ and $96 \\mathrm{~cm}$ from one end","At $72 \\mathrm{~cm}$ and $96 \\mathrm{~cm}$ from one end"],"answer":3,"solution":"Total length of the wire, $\\mathrm{L}=114 \\mathrm{~cm}$ $\\mathrm{n}_1: \\mathrm{n}_2: \\mathrm{n}_3=1: 3: 4$\nLet $\\mathrm{L}_1, \\mathrm{~L}_2$ and $\\mathrm{L}_3$ be the lengths of the three parts\nAs $\\mathrm{n} \\propto \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{~L}}$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\therefore \\quad \\mathrm{L}_1: \\mathrm{L}_2: \\mathrm{L}_3=\\frac{1}{1}: \\frac{1}{3}: \\frac{1}{4}=12: 4: 3 \\\\\n& \\therefore \\quad \\mathrm{L}_1=72 \\mathrm{~cm}\\left(\\frac{12}{12+4+3} \\times 114\\right) \\\\\n& \\mathrm{L}_2=24 \\mathrm{~cm}\\left(\\frac{4}{19} \\times 114\\right) \\\\\n& \\text { and } \\quad \\mathrm{L}_3=18 \\mathrm{~cm}\\left(\\frac{3}{19} \\times 114\\right)\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nHence the bridges should be placed at $72 \\mathrm{~cm}$ and $72+24=96 \\mathrm{~cm}$ from one end.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (23 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":44498,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>333</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>Hz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>500</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>Hz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>666</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>Hz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>753</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>Hz</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Frequency of the observer,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>330</mn><mn>0.5</mn></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>Hz</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>660</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>Hz</mi></math><br /><br />Velocity of person<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>km</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>18</mn></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>2.8</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math><br />According to Doppler effect, frequency heard by the person,<br /><br /><math><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>o</mi></mrow></msub><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>660</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>330</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2.8</mn></mrow><mn>330</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>Hz</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>666</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>Hz</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44397,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"For closed organ pipe\n$\\mathrm{f}_{\\mathrm{c}}=(2 \\mathrm{n}+1) \\frac{\\mathrm{v}}{4 \\ell}=\\frac{15 \\mathrm{v}}{4 \\ell}$\nFor open organ pipe\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{f}_{\\mathrm{o}}=(\\mathrm{n}+1) \\frac{\\mathrm{v}}{2 \\ell}=\\frac{8 \\mathrm{v}}{2 \\ell} \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{f}_{\\mathrm{c}}}{\\mathrm{f}_{\\mathrm{o}}}=\\frac{15}{16}=\\frac{\\mathrm{a}-1}{\\mathrm{a}} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{a}=16\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44502,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["(a) $190 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$180 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$220 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$200 \\mathrm{~cm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"According to question, tuning fork gives 1 beat/second with (N) $3^{\\text {rd }}$ normal mode. Therefore, organ pipe will have frequency $(256 \\pm 1) \\mathrm{Hz}$. In open organ pipe, frequency $\\mathrm{n}=\\frac{\\mathrm{NV}}{2 \\ell}$\nor, $255=\\frac{3 \\times 340}{2 \\times \\ell} \\Rightarrow \\ell=2 \\mathrm{~m}=200 \\mathrm{~cm}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":44393,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["Both $\\mathbf{A}$ and $\\mathbf{R}$ are true but $\\mathbf{R}$ is NOT the correct explanation of $\\mathbf{A}$","$\\mathbf{A}$ is true but $\\mathbf{R}$ is false","$\\mathbf{A}$ is false but $\\mathbf{R}$ is true","Both $\\mathbf{A}$ and $\\mathbf{R}$ are true and $\\mathbf{R}$ is the correct explanation of $\\mathbf{A}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Speed of sound in a medium depends on inertial and elastic properties as $v=\\sqrt{\\frac{B}{P}}$ for gases and $v=\\sqrt{\\frac{Y}{P}}$ for solids. Since the elastic property of solid happens to be many folds greater than that of gases, the speed of sound in solids i5 higher than in gases.\n\nAlso, bulk modulus of gases varies between 0 and $\\infty\\left(B=-v \\frac{d P}{d v}\\right)$ hence reason is false.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44465,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>15</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mo>Ae</mo><mi>x</mi></msup><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&#952;</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>Ae</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>v</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>&#952;</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>sin</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The given function should be in the form of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>&#177;</mo><mi>v</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>.</p><p>So, for travelling wave <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math>&nbsp;should be linear function of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>and&nbsp;should be finite and continuous for all values of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>.&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>15</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> linear function in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44507,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>GHz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>GHz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>GHz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>17</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>GHz</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>c</mi><msup><mi>f</mi><mi>&#8242;</mi></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>&#946;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#946;</mi></mrow></mfrac></msqrt><mi>&#160;</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mi>c</mi></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>f</mi><mi>&#8242;</mi></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>f</mi></mfrac><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfrac></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><msqrt><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msqrt><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>f</mi></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>f</mi><mi>&#8242;</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi>f</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>f</mi><mi>&#8242;</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1.73</mn><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mn>10</mn></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>f</mi><mi>&#8242;</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>17.3</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>GHz</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":44448,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Waves and Sound","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#8467;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>500</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#8467;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>550</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>11</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac></math><br />Thus, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math><br />Thus,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#8467;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>nv</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac></msqrt></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>500</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>900</mn><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null}]